{"key":"processedPost-12671193","value":{"id":12671193,"first":12671101,"last":12671205,"when":1275489192,"utime":"06/02/10 05:33 PM","content":"First of all, perlite doesn't create too much humidity.&nbsp; In fact, there's no such thing as too much humidity.&nbsp; Mushrooms fruit in the fog after rains in 100%.<br />You can't re-case.&nbsp; The mold was in your spawn and only sporulated on the surface.&nbsp; Toss it out.<br />I'd suggest building a <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Terrarium-Tek\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">shotgun terrarium</a>, or a larger humidity tent, but put lots of holes in it for fresh air.&nbsp; Stale air stimulates molds, fresh air stimulates mushroom mycelium.<br />Any holes you make are not CO2 vents.&nbsp; They're air vents.&nbsp; Any CO2 produced by the substrate mixes with the air, and both need to be vented and replaced.&nbsp; It's a common mistake by new growers to think CO2 will 'drain' out holes in the bottom, but this isn't the case.<br />RR","title":"Re: New soil layer for green mold contaminated casing"}}